As a financial advisor who's helped many early career physicians with their finances, I see the same costly mistake happen year after year. High earners contribute directly to a Roth IRA when their income exceeds the income limits. First, income limits make Roth contributions off limits for families earning more than $236,000 in 2025 or $150,000 for a single filer in 2025. Many high earners don't actually realize they're above the income limits when they make these contributions, but it turns out it creates a huge headache for themselves when they have to deal with these excess contributions. Second, high earners will oftentimes benefit most from contributing to their retirement plans at work. Think 401k plan or 403b. Contributing to these types of retirement plans allow them to reduce their taxable income during their peak earning years, which is when they need it most. Third, your investment account of choice should really fit into your overall financial plan. I once helped this OBGYN who was making over $500,000 a year by contributing the max to her 403b and maxing out the backdoor Roth IRA. She was still only at about a 6% savings rate for her retirement, which is not nearly enough to accomplish the goal for early retirement by age 50. So working together allowed me to find the next best place for her to be saving for her financial future. If you're interested in making simple and smart improvements with your finances, check out the free wealth building course I've prepared for you with the link in my bio.

Did you know that in the late 19th century, lynching was rampant, claiming countless lives? Ida B. Wells faced this horror and chose to fight back. Born into slavery in 1862, Wells grew up to become a fierce journalist. She uncovered shocking truths about the brutality of lynching in America. In 1892, after the lynching of three friends, Wells began her investigation. She found most victims were black men falsely accused of crimes. They tried to silence her with threats and violence. Her office was destroyed, but Ida didn't back down. She sharpened her pen and continued her battle. Wells published detailed reports, exposing lies and advocating for justice. She traveled, giving lectures and spreading awareness despite constant danger. Her work laid the foundation for the civil rights movement. Wells proved that fearless journalism could challenge systemic racism and provoke change. Ida's legacy reminds us that courage and truth can overcome oppression. Her relentless fight against lynching is a beacon of hope and justice. As Wells famously said, they tried to silence me with fear, but I sharpened my pen and fought back. Her words inspire us to continue the fight for equality.

From 1917 to 1948, British mandate Palestine witnessed profound political and cultural transformations within the Jewish community, or Yishab. The 1917 Balfour Declaration pledged British support for a Jewish national home, fueling Jewish immigration, aliyah, and urban growth. Political life flourished with the establishment of the Jewish Agency in 1929, led by figures like Kheim Weitzman and David Ben-Gurion, which coordinated settlement, defense, and diplomacy. The Haganah, a Jewish defense force, emerged to protect communities amid Arab Jewish tensions, especially during the 1929 riots in 1936 and 1939 Arab revolt. Culturally, Hebrew was revived as a spoken language, with schools, newspapers, and theaters fostering a modern Jewish identity. Institutions like the Technion and Hebrew University nurtured scientific and intellectual life. Kibbutzim and Moshevim pioneered collective agriculture, shaping social ideals. British immigration restrictions in the 1930s spurred clandestine efforts to rescue Jews fleeing Europe. The Yishab's resilience, organization, and cultural vibrancy laid the groundwork for the state of Israel's founding in 1948.

In the world of digital finance, Ripple is quietly reshaping how institutions trade on the blockchain. At the center of that transformation is something new. The XRPL permissioned DEX, often called Ripple's private decentralized exchange. The XRP ledger has always had a built-in decentralized exchange, one of the first in blockchain history. But this new version is different. It's designed for banks, fintechs, and regulated entities that need the speed and efficiency of blockchain, but with privacy, compliance, and control. Instead of an open public marketplace, the permissioned DEX introduces the idea of permissioned domains. Each domain is like a private trading floor inside the ledger. Only verified accounts can place or accept offers there. To gain access, participants hold a digital credential, a cryptographic proof that they've passed KYC or other compliance checks without ever exposing their personal information on chain. These permissioned order books are isolated from the public DEX. That means trades within them stay within a trusted network of verified users, while still settling directly on the XRP ledger, instantly, transparently, and without intermediaries. This hybrid design gives institutions the best of both worlds, blockchain efficiency with real-world accountability. Ripple calls it the bridge between decentralized finance and traditional finance. The technology behind it is already live in parts. On-chain credentials have been activated, and permissioned domains can be created on XRPL test networks today. Ripple and partners like SBI Group are exploring pilot use cases, setting the stage for fully regulated digital asset markets on XRPL. It's not just a new exchange. It's a new model for compliance-ready DeFi, where liquidity moves freely. But access is controlled, a private decentralized exchange built for the institutional era, fast verified, and ready for the future of finance. ChatGPT can make mistakes. Check important info.

Before you unleash AI into the world, you've got to ask, what damage could it do? That's where an impact assessment comes in. It's a process to map out all of the possible risks of an AI system. It examines ethical, legal, economic, and societal consequences before the system is deployed. The goal? Spot risks, understand them, and figure out how to reduce the bad stuff before it happens. For example, if a hiring AI might discriminate, the impact assessment reveals the issue early so that it can be fixed. In governance, this tool ensures AI systems are tested like crash dummies for cars. Risks exposed before real people get hurt. Impact assessments are AI's report cards. Just then, John saw another slot machine that had a faint glow coming from it. Without thinking, he chose that machine and sat down. He did the same thing. Took out a coin, rubbed it with his fingers, put it into the machine, and shouted loudly, hello! Then suddenly, the jackpot sound came, and lots of coins came out. Now Johns started to leave without taking any money. But a staff member stopped him and took him straight to the owner's office. The owner pulled out a big bag full of cash and gave it to Johns. He said, just promise me one thing, never come to my casino again. Then he called a driver and arranged for Johns to be sent home. As soon as Johns reached home, his wife opened the door, slapped him hard in anger, and snatched the bag from his hand. But when she opened it and saw all the bundles of cash inside, she realized that Johns had really hit the jackpot at the casino.

Hello, Views' King Harris, the son of hip-hop icons T.I. and Tiny, has spent the past few years trying to prove he's tougher than his upbringing. Born into wealth and fame, King's attempt to portray himself as street-certified has turned into one of the most public examples of image collapsing under reality. Everything came crashing down after a traffic stop in October 2024 spiraled into a full-blown scandal. Police pulled him over for swerving, immediately smelling weed and spotting a loaded gun on his hip. When they ran his name, an active warrant popped up from a past DUI case he failed to show up for. What followed was a mix of confusion, denial, and panic as King insisted he had no outstanding cases, only to realize he was caught in his own web of carelessness. The viral footage showed a nervous, lost young man, not the confident online persona he sold to millions. The arrest exposed how deeply King had fallen into the trap of pretending to be something he's not. Officers found multiple firearms in his car, including an AR-15-style rifle. Because of his prior juvenile felony, that alone could have landed him serious prison time. His attempts to talk his way out of the situation, admitting to having guns while baking police not to search, only made things worse. The internet devoured the footage, mocking the contradiction between his tough talk and frightened demeanor. He was extradited to another county, spent days behind bars, and by the time he was released on bond, the damage was already done.
